###Introduction
This assignment required our group to apply an Enterprise Risk Management (ERM) framework to a real-world acquisition scenario: Canada Life's 2026 acquisition of Santé Circle Health. The aim was to identify and assess key risks associated with the transaction and develop a structured Risk Calculation Sheet, a scored Risk Register, and Risk Heat Maps to support risk analysis and decision making.
For an acquisition of this scale, understanding and managing risk is essential. Mergers and acquisitions are among the most complex strategic initiatives organizations undertake, and research suggests that between 70% and 90% fail to achieve their expected value for shareholders (Bain & Company, 2024). As a result, a comprehensive risk assessment is necessary to identify potential challenges that could affect the success of the integration.
Our analysis identified risks across six categories: financial, operational, competitive, reputational, technical, and legal. Each risk was evaluated using a 1-to-5 scale for both likelihood and impact. The overall risk score was calculated by multiplying the likelihood and impact ratings, resulting in a score ranging from 1 to 25. Risks scoring between 15 and 25 were classified as High priority, those scoring between 9 and 14 as Medium priority, and those scoring between 1 and 8 as Low priority. The risks were then plotted on a heat map using likelihood on the vertical axis and impact on the horizontal axis to provide a visual representation of the organizations overall risk exposure.
The report is organized into four main sections. The first section presents the Risk Calculation Sheet and outlines the identified risks across all six categories. The second section explains the risk scoring methodology and includes the complete 18-risk register. The third section presents the Risk Heat Maps developed in Excel. Finally, the report concludes with key findings and recommended controls designed to support effective risk management throughout the acquisition and integration process.
Problem Statement
Canada Life's acquisition of Santé Circle Health is a strategically sound move, but it brings with it a set of risks that the organisation has not previously faced at this scale. Entering active healthcare service delivery means absorbing new operational complexity, a more sensitive data environment, and a competitive landscape that includes digital health disruptors with lower cost structures and faster innovation cycles.
Three pressures frame the risk landscape. Integration history is not encouraging, 70 to 90 percent of M&A deals fail to create shareholder value, and only 30 percent achieve projected synergy targets (Bain & Company, 2024). At the same time, Quebec's Law 25, fully in force since 2025, imposes strict health data privacy obligations with penalties reaching up to CAD $25 million or four percent of global revenue (OneTrust, 2025). And while Canada Life brings financial strength to this deal, Manulife's Vitality platform and Sun Life's digital health investments mean the merged entity enters the healthcare services market at a competitive disadvantage it will need to close quickly (KASE Insurance, 2026; HelloSafe, 2025).
This assessment identifies and scores 18 material risks across six categories using a 1-to-5 likelihood and impact scale, consistent with the COSO ERM framework. The goal is not to argue against the acquisition but to ensure that the risks it creates are understood clearly enough to be managed well.

